= Introduction
Gas Insulated Switchgear (GIS) describes equipment used in power systems where components are fully enclosed in a metal housing and pressurised with an insulating gas, commonly sulphur hexafluoride. In comparison to air-insulated lines (AIS), this can significantly reduce the size of substations.

The draw back of GIS is the introduced complexity of identifying and repairing faults due to the inaccessibility of the components. The second most common fault in GIS operation is particle defects. Particles suspended in the insulating gas or adhered to the conductors can cause partial discharge (PD) to occur; a localised electrical breakdown.

Present monitoring techniques detect the ultra-high frequency (UHF) or acoustic signals generated by PD @UFHvsAcoustic, however, these techniques are reactive. The novel microwave mechanical monitoring approach discussed in this project aims to detect particles before they lead to PD.
= Structure of GIS
The GIS studied for this project are busbars, a high-voltage (HV) inner conductor surrounded by insulating gas, completely enclosed in a cylindrical metal shell @franks2022gis. Regularly spaced along the GIS are antennas installed for PD monitoring @sensorPlacement. GIS have insulating spaces which hold the central conductor in place. However, for this project, the spacers are omitted and the GIS is capped at either end.
= GIS defects
Particle defects:
- The second most common defect type
- Account for 20% of all failures @internalDefects
- Can be free-floating in the gas insulation
- Can settle on support insulators
- Can be formed from the structure (protrusions)
- Can be introduced during manufacturing
- Also created during assembly or operation when parts rub against each other

Larger defects such as nuts or bolts can be shed by components during operation. The least common particle fault are protrusions from the HV conductors.

